Q4.

(a) Purpose of fork() and exec() System Calls
        1. fork()
              Creates a new child process by duplicating the parent process.
              Returns:
                  0 in the child process.
                  Child's PID in the parent process.
                  -1 if creation fails.
        2. exec()
              Replaces the current process with a new program.
              If successful, the new program starts executing and the old program is replaced.

b) Role of wait() System Call:
         1.wait() causes the parent process to wait until its child process finishes execution.
         2.It prevents the creation of zombie processes.
         3.Returns the Process ID (PID) of the terminated child.

c) 

#include <stdio.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>
int main()
{
    pid_t pid;
    pid = fork();
    if (pid < 0){
        printf("Fork failed.\n");
    }
    else if (pid == 0){
        // Child process
        printf("Child is executing a new program...\n");
        execl("/bin/ls", "ls", NULL);
    }
    else
    {
        // Parent process
        wait(NULL);
        printf("Child process completed.\n");
    }
 return 0;
}

